63
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:47,000
stir the boiling liquid in a jar of molten iron for hours.

64
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
The titanic effort was crowned with success.

65
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:55,000
In 1902, scientists obtained

66
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,000
a decigram of pure radio chloride.

67
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:00,000
The appearance of that white powder

68
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
was similar to that of table salt,

69
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
but the light radiating from it was so bright

70
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
that it could be read near the tubes

71
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
in which the radio salt was stored.

72
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Impressed by the extraordinary work of the physicists,

73
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Vladimir Mayakovsky later compared

74
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:20,000
the process of obtaining radio with poetry.

75
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:24,000
You have to work a whole year to get a gram.

76
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Despite its precarious nature,

77
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
the scientists did not patent their discoveries.

78
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Marie said,

79
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,000
the radio should not enrich anyone.

80
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:37,000
This element belongs to the world.

81
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
For their work on radioactivity,

82
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Marie and Pierre Curie were awarded

83
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1903.

84
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:51,000
